<h2>Arizona Incentives & Rebates</h2>

<p>Arizona homeowners have access to substantial federal, state, and utility incentives that significantly reduce the cost of solar panel and HVAC system installations. The federal Solar Investment Tax Credit (ITC) provides a 30% tax credit for solar installations completed through 2032, with the credit percentage stepping down to 26% in 2033 and 22% in 2034 before expiring for residential installations. This credit applies to the total system cost, including equipment, installation, and related expenses, and can be carried forward to future tax years if the credit exceeds current tax liability.</p>

<p>Arizona offers a Solar Equipment Sales Tax Exemption that eliminates the state's 5.6% sales tax on solar energy devices and their installation, providing additional savings of \$650-1,600 on typical residential solar installations. The state also provides a Solar Property Tax Exemption that prevents solar installations from increasing property tax assessments, ensuring that added home value from solar doesn't result in higher property taxes. These state-level incentives complement federal programs to create some of the most favorable solar economics in the United States.</p>

<p>Arizona Public Service (APS) offers time-of-use rates and net metering programs that can maximize solar savings for customers. The utility's Saver Choice Max plan provides higher rates during peak hours (3-8 PM) when solar production may be declining, encouraging battery storage adoption. APS also offers rebates for high-efficiency HVAC systems, with incentives up to \$1,000 for qualifying heat pumps and air conditioners that meet efficiency requirements. Salt River Project (SRP) provides similar programs for their service territory, including renewable energy incentives and demand-based rate structures that reward energy efficiency.</p>

<p>Many Arizona municipalities offer additional incentives, expedited permitting, and reduced fees for solar installations. Cities like Phoenix, Tucson, and Scottsdale have streamlined solar permitting processes that reduce installation timelines and costs. Some local utilities and energy efficiency programs provide additional rebates for HVAC upgrades, smart thermostats, and whole-house energy efficiency improvements that complement solar installations.</p>

